rom 4. to infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT 307 29 "kp - why from 2 to infinity??" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "C.  The intervals
 of this graph are negative from 2.000000000 to 4." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
"> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "subs(x=0,d1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 "6#\"$G\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 190 "D.  The right si
de of this graph is positive down to 2, then negative down from 2 to3.
5(approx.)and negative up from 3.5 approx. up to 4.  The graph is then
 positive up from 4 to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 71 "The
 left side of the graph is positive up from the y axis to infinity. " 
}}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  P
olynomials:  Local extreme values and monotonicity.  Beyond informatio
n of the type gathered above about intercepts and signs of a polynomia
l,  other important information can be determined from the so called \+
\"critical points\" of a polynomial.  The critical points of a polynom
ial are the intercepts of its derivative.  Since the derivative of a f
unction at a point represents the slope of the tangent line to the gra
ph of the that function at the point, then the intercepts of the deriv
ative are places where the the tangent lines to the function are flat,
 i.e., are horizontal lines.  At such places the graph is neither incr
easing nor decreasing.  Elsewhere the graph must be either increasing \+
or decreasing.  For a polynomial, local extreme values (local maximums
 or local minimums) must occur at the intercepts of the derivative.  \+
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "     \+
The follwing features are important in analyzing the graph of a polyno
mial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "
     f.   critical points of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
99 "                      For a polynomial these are the intercepts of
 the derivative of the polynomial" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "    \+
 g.    local maximum points of the graph of a function y = f(x)" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 274 "                      These are points (
x,y) on the graph of the function for which the y-value is locally the
 largest value of the function.  Nearby values on the graph are lower.
  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (x,y) must be a critical \+
point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     h.   loc
al minimum points of the graph of a function y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "                      These are points (x,y) on the
 graph of the function for which the y-value is locally the smallest v
alue of the function.  Nearby values on the graph are higher.  For a p
olynomials the x-value of the point (x,y) must be a critical point of \+
the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     i.    regions (i
ntervals) in the domain of the function where the values of the functi
on are increasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                   \+
    Those regions where the graph rises as the graph is traversed from
 left to right.  For a continuous function, and in particular for poly
nomials, these regions are bounded by the critical points and may stre
tch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     j.    reg
ions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of the
 function are decreasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "            \+
           Those regions where the graph falls as the graph is travers
ed from left to right.  For a continuous function, and in particular f
or polynomials, these regions are bounded by the critical points and m
ay stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 275 "For each of the following polynomials,  provid
e a graph of the polynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally repre
sent the features of the graph.  Include the graph of the deriviative \+
of the polynomial on the plot.   Plot the function in red and the derv
iative in green.   " }{TEXT 269 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 89 ", for each poly
nomial find each of the above ten graphcial characteristics (a.  thru \+
j.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "a.
